"EO DIE quo consuerat intervallo hostes sequitur et milia passuum tria ab eorum castris castra ponit."|"eo die. So hie dies, iUe dies, is dies. In these phrases dies is masc. with rare exceptions. But the Romans preferred the fern, ill ad hanc diem; ad illam, earn, quam diem; ex hac, ex ilia, ex ea die ; qua ex die. A good instance of this distinction in usage is I. 6, diem dicunt qua die ... \ is dies erat, &c. NOTES."

"NOT FOUND"|"1. 8. defuerit. Obs. perf. Subj. in place of the ordinary imperf. It expresses more than the imperf. * that there was no time either then or after; * but it is difficult to feel and express clearly the difference between the perf. and imperf. Subj. in these cases. The perfect is very rare. Caesar uses it seldom, Cicero very seldom, Sallust not at all, Livy not often : see note on p. 37,1.1; cp. v. 15, 54; vir. 17."

"NOT FOUND"|"1. 26. inciderint. Occido and recido are the only compounds of cado which possess a supine."

